From 37c61beed9884e133aba928caf536fe60585c6bc Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Dan on Selwyn <dan@awto.au>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 10:31:38 +1000
Subject: [PATCH] lib: translate iomem_copy to Rust (linux-rs TU 32)

memset_io/memcpy_fromio/memcpy_toio: word-at-a-time __iomem set/copy,
handling unaligned lead-in/trailing bytes one at a time and the bulk in
sizeof(long) chunks. Uses the RAW (unordered, no barrier, no endian
swap) __raw_read*/__raw_write* MMIO accessors, distinct from the
already-wrapped ordered readb/writeb family -- new rust_helper_raw_*
shims added to rust/helpers/io.c (rule 0014/0016: these are arch
static inlines in arch/riscv/include/asm/mmio.h, invisible to bindgen,
with real hardware ordering semantics that rule out reimplementing
them in pure Rust). kernel::io::{Io, Mmio} deliberately not used here:
that abstraction is bounds-checked register-width access to a
known-size region; these three are unbounded bulk-copy primitives
Mmio itself would sit on top of, the same shape as memcpy/memset
against __iomem memory. Every #ifdef CONFIG_64BIT branch preserved
via #[cfg(...)] in both the translation and its shims.

Verified via a new tier-2.5 differential oracle (bench/diff_iomem_copy.{c,rs}):
7500 randomized cases across all 8 sub-word alignment offsets,
byte-identical. No dedicated upstream KUnit suite exists for this
file (same as memweight/checksum), so integrated without --kunit;
all 16 existing suites remain green post-integration, INIT REACHED.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
